06159nam a22010095i 9783110613674DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106136747 a10.1515/97831106136742doi  a(DE-B1597)498191  a(OCoLC)1138537249  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPR1365.T23 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a900  aHK 1340qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/50158:1 aSchön, Theresa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Cosmography of Man :bCharacter Sketches in "The Tatler" and "The Spectator" /cTheresa Schön. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (VII, 349 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHallesche Beiträge zur Europäischen Aufklärung : Schriftenreihe des Interdisziplinären Zentrums für die Erforschung der europäischen Aufklärung der Martin-Luther-Universität Halle-Wittenberg ,x0948-6070 ;v61  aDiss.cUniv.Halle-Wittenbergd2017.00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Character and Knowledge in Early Eighteenth-Century English Periodicals -- tChapter Two. Epistemic Categories -- tChapter Three. The Tatler: The ‘Individual’ Gaze -- tChapter Four. The Spectator: A Community of Modern Observers -- tChapter Five. Ordering Characterological Knowledge in The Tatler and The Spectator -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tWorks Cited -- tTable of Figures0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDesigned to reform contemporary British society, Joseph Addison and Richard Steele’s The Tatler (1709-1711) and The Spectator (1711-1712, 1714) rely heavily on the representation of contemporary manners. In shaping such behavioural images, the authors made use of the satirical character sketch. Their character sketches (re)create social interactions between fictionalised representatives of moral types of men and women located in contemporary London. This study examines how Addison and Steele employed the character sketch to create a ‘cosmography’ of (wo)man by actively engaging with the observational approaches of contemporary naturalists. Addison and Steele adapted distinctly empirical methods (e.g. induction and deduction, note taking, repeated and collective observation) and appropriated the (medico-legal) case study to communicate and disseminate socio-moral knowledge. At the same time, the character sketch served them as a means to establish a taxonomic order of the socio-moral knowledge conveyed in the texts. The study sheds new light on the literary techniques and the methodological frameworks of two journals essentially associated with the British - and the European - Enlightenment.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCharacters and characteristics in literature. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 4aCharakter. 4aSpectator (Zeitschr.). 4aTatler (Zeitschr.). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  a"The Spectator".  a"The Tatler".  aCharacter sketch.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE  DG 2019 Englishz978311061685908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eB